		<h3 class="piece_header"> Introduction </h3>		

		This poem has been described as being about snowboarding, it is no more about snowboarding than ‘The Waste Land’ is about Reading. If you choose to declaim this poem — for thus must it be read — do not wear a black polo-neck, even ironically, unless you are also Steve Jobs. <br> <br>

		If you prefer to attend a true Lyric festival instead check out their web site here. <br> <br>

		<h3 class="piece_header"> LYRIK FESTIVAL </h3>		

		Poets that have never seen the snow sit in the dark, in concentrated rows, wear black in spring, sniffle, cough, blow noses but listen intently to the mobile muse — she bids them notice ironies, life’s little hurts and smaller surprises. The poets make notes and struggle for strangeness, subtle devices. <br> <br>

		For this she lends them her eyes? Dream on, poets that wear black and move words on stage slower than Death moves pawns when losing at chess, for you come here, in black, to the black room, to bury Life not to praise Her. Oh poets, that have never seen the snow, follow me! <br> <br>

		Run out of the fire exit tonight: My ’84 535 is packed with spare t-shirts, second-hand jackets, balaclava hats and excessively large boots; and we’ll drive all night, sleep in a lay-by, and then we’ll go up, in a gondola, before the light, right to the top. We will bind our legs onto our boards, jump up, to turn around, and start over the lip, onto the piste, with groomed ice-ridges cracking under our edges, like a runaway train that’s left the track and suddenly, floating over powder, we’ll carve a sign down the mountain, a chain of commas, easily read, easily parsed. We’ll gasp at the speed, our mouths blown wide, our legs scared solid our pupils wide — our eyes shot glacier-blue and wild. At the bottom we’ll incongruously hop-jump together and hug and yell with one voice: Fuck depression! Let’s write about THAT!
		</p>
