	<h3 class="piece_header"> Passed Over </h3>		
		<h3 class="piece_header"> I Heptonstall Churchyard </h3>		
		<p>
		"Asa Benveniste ~ Foolish enough to have been a poet" <br> <br>
		I booked my plot here before I knew about her. <br>
		I’d heard she wrote, heard she moved down south to Devon, <br>
		then to London. Poor thing. I never met her. But, today, <br>
		as everyday, it isn’t me the visitors travel to see. <br> <br>
		Those PhD pilgrims, the striking teens, <br>
		stand by her and are lost in the wind, <br>
		thinking, one day every year the moon  <br>
		will rise over that Yew. <br> <br>
		This leafless afternoon Starlings sing, all jumbled <br>
		as usual, Now, they are imitating Curlews <br>
		curdling, from behind the corner  <br>
		of the roofless church. <br> <br>

		<h3 class="piece_header"> II Pére Lachaise </h3>		
		"Security guard at the grave: ‘N’est-ce pas une poubelle" <br> <br>

		We buy an offering from the minibar <br>
		a libation for peace  <br>
		dropped off at The Last Whiskey Bar. <br> <br>
		‘James James Morrison Morrison,  <br>
		wanted to be a poet’  <br>
		When is ever what we have good enough? <br> <br>
		From the bare planes a Blackcap <br>
		is singing, singing, singing a well of songs <br>
		that would wash us all away <br>
		even if no-one was listening. <br> <br>

		<h3 class="piece_header"> West Cemetery, Amherst. </h3>		
		"Called Back" <br> <br>
		I had the ruby-throated <br>
		humming like a wheel – <br>
		my quill — distilled it in my drawer <br>
		written with safe white ink. <br><br>
		and wrapped in twine. <br>
		It was the white on white <br>
		that let it pale, <br><br>
		–every letter — every space — every rail – <br>
		the tracks will take you — Prisoner —  <br>
		with no report of Bail.  <br>
		The letters of black-inked rejection – <br><br>
		Six letters — a thousand words – <br>
		No secret garden is there, but had a Wall. <br>
		White written on White — the right <br>
		of de-selection. <br><br>
		Firmament of maples lawns and birches <br>
		Window sill — I am — small — as they are – <br>
		and in my drawer bedecked — evanescent — bright.
		</p>
